name: Sam Rubin
bio: KTLA - TV Entertainment Anchor. "Today” 9 Network Australia, ITV "This Morning."  Emmy Award Winning Host. Book a call with me  intro.co/SamRubin

social_posts.post_text: Just out of the ABBA Arena in London - very emotional and unusual evening with the Swedish superstars. The most technically advanced concert you have likely ever seen. Crystal clear perfect video - all sorts of unique lighting and other effects - and ABBA themselves singing and playing and dancing. The only thing missing - ABBA themselves. The whole thing is a state of the art digital/hologram thing. They ask that no pictures or video be taken inside the theater - so as not to spoil the surprise. And the whole thing is startling. They are there, except they are not there. If you can get past that - certain songs- most notably “Gimme Gimme Gimme” “The Winner Takes It All” and of course “Dancing Queen” are amazing. And Agnetha and Anni-Frid , depicted in their mid 30’s I think are so gorgeous it is beyond belief. Something happens at the very end that actually made me tear up.. This show can run forever and probably will. Really creative. My only gripe - they didn’t sing “The. Name Of The Game” nor “Super Trouper” - which would have caused me to openly weep. I paid about $100 for my ticket, well worth it. I wonder if any other group has both the catalogue and fan base to support such an effort. At the very very end about 50 people take bows - my guess is that they were the computer programmers and coders that made the whole thing happen.  I am still pondering what it all means and if this is the way we want to use suoer advanced technology for our entertainment.

So much fun to fly all the way across the Atlantic and share with all of the United Kingdom what I enjoy doing so much back home in Los Angeles. Happy to offer a Holiday Entertainment Preview today on @thismorning with my friends @alisonhammond55 and @radioleary_ . It is cold and very Christmas-y in London today, but super warm feelings on the set.

39 degrees and only the small towel I brought from home. I underestimated the genuine challenge of taking a cold Water plunge - but I have lived to tell the tale. The great @da_rulk has helped so many stars and first responders and he says there are many benefits to this ice cold encounters.  We’ll see.

If you are obsessed with #gotgvol3 - you are not alone. Folks @fandango say it is the #1 most anticipated blockbuster of 2023. Speaking of @guardiansofthegalaxy our pals @sunkistcitrus have a special treat for the season - their best navels in a special GOTG box. At @walmart and a bunch of places for the Holidays.

Pass the Kleenex. Has this most excellent new @hallmarkchannel movie “A Holiday Spectacular” actually surpassed my formally favorite “Snow Bride” as the best Hallmark Holiday movie ever. Special cameo from Ann-Margret no less. “Dad you can’t be crying over this one too” - as my somewhat exasperated son said as he saw me dabbing my eyes. Maggie comes from a rich family who are planning an arranged marriage for their daughter to the dreaded Mawell. Sensing her only chance to break free from the shackles of wealth and privilege. Maggie hightails it to New York and to pursue her dream of becoming a Rockette - and meets the anti-Maxwell. A middle class guy named John who is supposed to take over the family grocery store but actually wants to become a photo-journalist. Can Maggie and John overcome the initial expectations of their parents and find love and professional fulfillment? Couldn’t think of a better way to spend Christmas Eve.

“Great Gift - I would have loved it” are the final words from @ktlasam in this “year end” package - and her words turn out to be spot on for me. This year - ALL of these years - have been a gift. And I never forget for one second that I am on the receiving end of your generosity. Thanks so much for watching our show and allowing all of us these remarkable opportunities. I have now done this job for more than half of my entire life and I wouldn’t have it any other way. 2022 has certainly had more than its share of sadness and challenges but also as you will see here there were many moments of laughter and joy. Here’s hoping 2023 really tips the scales towards even more of the things that bring us all happiness. A safe and happy and healthy New Year to one and all. Thanks again for making each so memorable for me.

Oberlin, Ohio is a long way from Southern California but the influence of @oberlincollege certainly more than covers the miles. I felt lucky and really enjoyed my own college experience here in town at Occidental - but my eldest daughter like many of her friends elected to go farther from home - all the way to Oberlin. The school also has a very strong supporter in actor @edhelms . We spoke about the school today and you can simply see and hear Ed beam as he talks about it. My second daughter is in her last semester of her senior year and has also had a great college experience. These are real privileges, and I never forget that. Neither does a really grateful Ed Helms.

I have borrowed my son’s security blanket stuffed animal friend “Kiki” who has been part of our family since 2007 - because it is an extra early bedtime for me - why? Because for the first time in several years @theacademy is having the Oscar Nominations announced as a live event. That’s a good sign of trying to bring back some excitement and fun to the proceedings. The downside - up at 3 am Tuesday morning. Join us @ktlamorningnews for our @ktla_entertainment fantastic coverage of all things Oscars - live reports in our 5 am hour - nominee reaction all morning long. @moviemantz on hand to offer his expertise. Join us bright and early. In the meantime - good night from me and Kiki.
. Now @thekidlaroi here at @gdayusa and their amazing annual gala here in Los Angeles. Can’t wait to see @deltagoodrem later tonight.

I don’t even know where to begin. After two incredible concerts in Las Vegas I am devoting my entire life to the continued exploration of live talent. I will get to the phenomenal @bryanadams who was at the beautiful Encore theater at @wynnlasvegas in a later post. For now can we just talk about what was close to what pure divinity must be like @adele and show number 20 of her “Weekends with Adele” series @caesarspalace . Beyond. The video I am sharing here is how she opened the show. “Hello” of course and then a few other numbers with just her purely from heaven voice and piano. And the show could have stopped right there. It is almost a religious experience to hear someone with such exceptional talent just deliver. Just show in the most effortless way what she has. But Adele was just getting warmed up. A full 2 hour show with every possible Vegas bell and whistle - but artistically selected. There is so much thought and care and love clearly poured into this show. Adele herself quipped about the very high ticket price saying the tickets were so expensive she was only given two for herself for each show. I paid $600 each for a pair of what I would describe as fairly good seats. But I think anywhere in the entire building would have worked - the show is that intimate and good. I also recognize those ticket prices are simply deal breakers for so many people - but if you can swing it I thought it was beyond worth it. You see and hear every penny on the stage.  It is a very lavish production. Press reports say after this residency is over Adele plans to spend several years devoted to academic pursuits. She has earned whatever break she wants. And talent this good and this precious maybe needs to be distributed in small batches. I sat next to a mother and daughter and the girl was probably in her mid-teens and she was just beaming the entire time. Like she was being transported to some place that was extraordinary special to her. It must be an incredible blessing to be able to move so many people in such a fantastic and personal way. Wow. Also a quick shout out to my pals at @palms . Such an easy place to stay. 10 minute cab ride to Caesars. Also fantastic and easy.

On the show tomorrow I am going to talk and show some videos from my quick Vegas live music performance getaway. Still thinking about the @adele show a full 48 hours after I saw it. And still thinking about this new Vegas restaurant which I could not have enjoyed more. Vetri Cucina is a new marvel @palms . First I love the room. On the 56th floor with a breathtaking all-city view of the strip, and completely right sized. 75 guests total. A perfect number which enables all diners to enjoy the view. What you are seeing quickly gives way to an appreciation of what you are eating. Marc Vetri is a James Beard award winning chef who operates a legendary restaurant in Philadelphia. Whatever he is doing right there he replicates here. Exceptional Italian food and the small plate photo I share here of a Sweet Onion Crepe was brilliantly described as sharing the same aroma of onion that you often encounter when you walk into an In and Out Burger. The similarities end there. It is an exceptional dish. Every bite was great and the room is so great and so romantic I am seriously considering a Valentine’s Day (night) return. I am always happy to receive a restaurant recommendation before *everybody* hears about it. That’s what this is. Also, happily, prices not insane for a place of this caliber. And the service - second to none. I really loved the whole experience here.
null
null

On an especially chilly Valentine’s Night - a warm keepsake from a great December getaway with the Mrs - getting extra mushy by adding the music from the first dance at our wedding. We had a great time at the beautiful @veanewportbeach and we’re lucky - we have a great time everyday. Hope you are enjoying your Valentines Day with someone special - and if today is a solo outing that is okay too - you are special enough.

I think the way this particular photo is shot has indicated our @ktla_entertainment department priorities on this - another really Happy Birthday for me. The real life me and all the wonderful decorations are sort of blurred in the background while the @sprinklescupcakes version of me is front and center and as clear as a bell.  Between family and friends, colleagues and viewers, I am supported beyond measure and incredibly appreciative of so many well wishes. As a general rule people are very nice to me , and I am always mindful of that kindness. In a good way, it was really overwhelming today.

Bow-WOW. Fantastic pet adoption event happening today, Sunday, until 3 pm @beverlyhillsporsche_ rooftop. Dealership is in West Los Angeles at Camden and Santa Monica Blvd. Our own passionate pet person @kaceymontoya is there with her @fixnfidos group. Lots of food - pets - cool pet toys - great auction. A total scene. Pop by if you can until 3 pm today!

Usher understands.  We had some laughs amidst all the rain this morning during a promo for our ticket giveaway to see @usher in Las Vegas. When I interviewed Usher in person a few months ago I wore what I thought was a super stylish Hawaiian shirt from @tbahama Tommy Bahama. My colleagues did not feel the same way. Who is right? Do you like the threads or do I need to hit the mall. Thanks as always to Usher for being a good sport.

Maybe this is the very best way to acknowledge this supposed “National Day Of Hate.” We just came back from a lovely Bat Mitzvah. So many traditional celebrations were disrupted by the pandemic and just as people are coming back to cherished opportunities to get together - we were emailed tempered warnings about potential for problems on this day. Thankfully nothing dire has taken place. Instead a warm and wonderful evening celebrating rituals that have endured for thousands of years. Congratulations to our friend Lily for her special day - made even more special by acting as a demonstration of pure love on a day that was pre planned by some to celebrate the opposite.
null

Quite the scene here @yaamava . This is place is booming beyond belief. Excited to laugh with @jimgaffigan in just a few minutes - and the casino floor is absolutely buzzing. Maybe I don’t get out of the house much on Friday nights. Super happy celebratory vibe here tonight.

After all the wet weather and super hectic nature of “Awards Season” people need a break. So many upsetting headlines out of certain places in Mexico - but the folks @vloscabos assure me, and I believe them, that Cabo is entirely safe. There are certain geographical qualities to Cabo that contribute to its safety. And there are some great deals. My daughter and a few college senior pals enjoyed Spring Break there earlier this week - and I popped down briefly to chaperone. Beautiful weather, beautiful spirit, beautiful everything and some great deals. To that end - this @aero all first class/nearly private jet experience is easy and remarkable. Fly super quick out of Van Nuys to a private terminal in Cabo. (They also go to Sun Valley and Aspen) . And unlimited snacks and meals from @erewhonmarket . Super special and personal service. And $250 off a flight with the code AEROTOCABO . Fine print - carrier terms and conditions apply.  Not fine print - several carriers offer regular non-stop service and this costs more. But if time and privacy and convenience are of high value to you - this is a great way to go.

Best twofer ever. Spring Training and Spiritual Renewal. My friend Pretentious Steve has brought a plethora of pals on Spring Training trips for decades. My son and I caught on a few years ago and this might be our best trip ever. The bright and mild Arizona weather is making for spectacular conditions including the skies and sunsets. We just had a foul ball land about 6 seats away. Earlier today we paid a visit to my nephew @green1andy Andy who is Rabbi with the Or Tzion Congregation in Scottsdale. He is pleased to preside over a vibrant and thriving Jewish community that he says has grown during the pandemic as many families from California and elsewhere have relocated here. The bima in a synagogue is not a place one would normally take a picture I suppose, but it helps if you know the management. I couldn’t be prouder of him and all he has accomplished, and the numerous people that he is serving.  An abundance of blessing of all sorts today and tonight.

Getting there is half the fun. To gear up for the arduous adventure ahead - happily aboard @qatarairways and eager to experience their amazing QSuite service non-stop from SFO to Doha. Daily service from LAX too. By the way - lesson to be learned - the international terminal in San Francisco is world class. The city has well publicized woes, but wow did they build a completely first class easy to navigate terminal. Off to a great start. About to pop on the PJ’s and enjoy a needed snooze on the way to Kathmandu.

Hello from Nepal. Sleeping tonight in the shadow of “Fishtail” mountain - the locals call it Machha Puchhre. A mere 6,993 meters high. We are in the foothills of the Annapurna mountains getting acclimated for a few days before we head over to “the Everest side.” So far the terrain is not vastly dissimilar from hikes I have taken in California. What is different is the advantage that a “world away” perspective offers. When I tried to explain my occupation to one of our guides I asked - “Do any movie stars from Hollywood matter to you?” His quick reply - “Not at all.” Also in what appears to be some very challenging circumstances people here live in great harmony. Lessons to be learned both from the mountains and from the people here who call the mountains home.

This is what it is like to wake up at 11,200 feet with the Himalayas - not as towering mountains - but as your neighbors. Today is our “rest day” a welcome chance to take all@of this in. This is a trip I never would have planned or picked on my own - but I am very glad to be here.

Happy New Year from Nepal. It is 2080 here, and in many ways this country is 67 years ahead of us. Some things are timeless of course, in the lower right hand corner that is in fact Mount Everest peering over another towering peak. Lower left might be one of my very favorite photos - one of the native Nepalese, Divya, who was so genuinely glad to see our group as we hiked into the mountain lodge where she worked. There are places around the world with fancier service - but I am hard pressed to find a place where all the service is so very personal - where there is such a sincere exchange between travelers and those who take enormous pride in making their trip better. Lastly up top our posse including our guide Niraj - who put us through our paces - and led us to places I never imagined I could ever get to, and moreover enjoy for several days on end. It takes some time to come down from 11,000+ feet high, and I think also some time to fully appreciate all the extraordinary experiences we have shared and the lessons learned from those experiences.

A close shave. Now perhaps the single most difficult aspect of a long trip home. The re-entry. For two-plus weeks all the things I would normally do - I haven’t done. I haven’t even seen a television set. My laptop - which I usually have open for a few hours daily - has been closed and untouched. And try as I might to get my 10,000 steps in - that goal is more often than not unachieved when I am back in Los Angeles. Here in Nepal we averaged 20,000+ steps per day, and some other really helpful and healthful routines that I hope I can keep up with. One other change, I left my Gillette Fusion 5 razor at home. So step one in the repatriation process - I desperately needed a shave. Mission accomplished thanks to the skilled hands and single blade straight razor magic of the barber pictured here. There will be other adjustments - some less traumatic. Hot water whenever I want it, (along with tap water you can drink without worry), fully paved roads, and all the reliable services that so many of us take for granted. I really loved it here, but there is a huge difference between our first world daily experiences in the USA and many aspects of the third world that are present here. But, and this is also worth a mention, many of our worst ills, most notably crime are almost completely absent in Nepal. The culture is such and the mutual struggle of so many other hardships are such that people here don’t steal from one another or assault one another. How peace can so easily coexist with, by USA standards, what would seem like lots of deprivation is one of things I thought about in the barbershop chair just a few hours ago. There will be much more to process in the days ahead.  Eager now to make my way home.

When it is good - there is nothing better. Happy to be part of a sell-out crowd that roared tonight @comedyandmagicclub with one huge name - @paulreiserofficial . He is working out material for a new comedy special his first in decades - Paul says “I like to space them apart.” Great set and then Paul is followed by a new-to-me very funny lady named @ejthecomic Erin Jackson. Hilarious energy and genuinely funny things to say. Also new-to-me @ryangoodcase who is delightfully odd and really funny.  Feels so good to laugh alongside a few hundred others.

Eagle Project.  Many Scouts, my son among them, are spending this Saturday and many additional hours working on their Eagle Projects. The basic idea is as simple as it is powerful. Identify and plan and build a worthwhile project that will benefit the greater community at large. My son is working on a bookshelf/cubbie system that, with any luck will provide a secure home for 50 backpacks for a local and very well deserving youth club. Our friends @airtaskerusa helped us find a fantastic professional wood-working expert to show us all the things we did not know - which was quite a bit. Happily, and it is a series of great life-lessons, the Scouts are doing most of the heavy lifting and we should have this project finished and installed fairly soon. Many @homedepot visits later, we have all the elements, the wherewithal and the elbow grease required to finish the job.
A mother knows.  Just a little World Exclusive. @taylorswift ‘s new squeeze is another Brit. We confirm the romance with the new Mister’s mom.
null

Bewildering. In a business full to overflowing with adjectives, I have never heard that B-word used to describe a reaction to seeing a film. @melissamccarthy here on the new “The Little Mermaid” a movie she loves and she loves being in. Watch a portion of our chat here. Full convo @ktla_entertainment

The day before the big day. An incredibly touching Baccalaureate Service on the afternoon before my daughter Rory and 400+ other smart seniors put on their caps and gowns and take that very big walk. A tip of the Mortar Board to Professor David Suggs who is retiring after 35 years of service and education - and who gave an especially moving address this afternoon. He quoted Samuel Beckett and the famous lines he wrote: “Ever tried. Ever failed. No matter. Try again. Fail again. Fail better.” And as I took in the professors words and this incredibly beautiful setting with the sun darting in and out from a partially cloudy sky - what struck me most about the college experience is where else are you provided the opportunity to simply think. Think about your subject material. Think about more frivolous matter. Just stare at the sky and think. I am guilty of this and maybe you are too - we are so “busy” rushing about we never take quiet time to think things through. Maybe that is the lesson I didn’t quite learn in college but am taking away this weekend in an especially pastoral college setting. It could not be lovelier here and the Professor referred to the campus as a sacred place - and I think  he is right.  So glad that Rory, her mom and I have all been able to take it in.

From scooting across the floor to walking across the stage to get her college diploma. I was really moved by my daughter’s graduation ceremony this weekend. It is a genuine privilege to be able to to go to college and if you are lucky enough to be able to send your kid(s) there too.

The great @buzzycohenofficial graced our @ktlamorningnews stage today with true “insider” wisdom. And the answer is - Buzzy has a new “all about Jeopardy” podcast which I am certainly going to listen to. Great guy.

Here we go again, again. This Summer’s Scouting “High Adventure” will take my son and I and our crew to the legendary Philmont camp sort of near Cimarron, New Mexico. In the meantime an 8 mile “practice hike” today with fairly full backpacks in the Santa Monica mountains. We have so many great local trails. This has been a big year of treks for me. In Nepal we didn’t really have to carry anything. Now with the Scouts we each carry all our own gear the whole way. I have spoken to adults my age who remember their Philmont visit when they were in their teens. I am really looking forward to my first visit later this month with a mix of both excitement and a touch of trepidation - 11 nights out in the wild.

Peace at last. Fun to spend time with my colleagues and new BFF’s @abc7george and @amandasalas on way home from @pixar junket for new @pixarelemental movie. Good film and great friends. Amanda a bit of a social media expert says “reels” is the best way to go - who am I to doubt her.
Here is the real story on what is happening with the Golden Globes.

Happy Father’s Day from our Scouting “High Adventure” at Philmont. Today we left base camp and began our trek somewhere near Kit Carson’s trading post on the original Santa Fe Trail. As our crew learned all about map navigation - I couldn’t help but delight in the extraordinary skies here. Beautiful and devious too. In a 45 minute time span things went from incredibly beautiful, to moderate rain to shockingly intense hail, and back to beautiful again - we experienced it all first hand as we were hiking at the time. More memory making tomorrow. I take such pleasure and pride in my three daughters and one son. And on a trip like this with a dozen dads and moms watching over more than 40 boys and girls from our troop - I am again reminded what a pleasure it is to be a parent and how incredibly fast they all grow up. My Dad, in his fashion, was deeply devoted to my two sisters and me but it would have never occurred to him to go on a trip like this - and as a kid - I never would have asked to go. It just wasn’t on our radar at all. For my son and I - and for the 20,000+ plus kids that will experience Philmont this summer - I am so glad we are immersed in it now.

What distinguishes a special experience? Was it the 11+ hours we spent hiking today or the 10.5 miles we covered, including a near 3 mile accent straight up to get to the top of Mount Phillips - or, as it turned out, worse - the decent on incredibly rocky trails. A very memorable day in the South Country of @philmontscoutranch . I vaguely recall taking a shower about 8 days ago - and apparently our next stop - 8+ miles away - will have hot showers. I may burst into tears when I go under the spigot at some point Friday afternoon.  This whole trip has been really hard - in terms of the pure physicality of the hikes and the hills and these pesky rocks. But it has also been exceptionally worthwhile. Meeting like-minded and dedicated moms and dads - and of course the scouts themselves - so many of them really rising to the occasion. It’s that unique duality. This is really killing me and I wouldn’t miss it for the world.
null

A recurring theme. 70+ miles. I can’t accurately estimate all the elevation up and down - but I can offer this happy and unexpected result. We all made it. 4 grown-ups and 8 kids on a 12 night trek deep into the backcountry of @philmontscoutranch .That is just our crew. Our entire troop had over 50 participants,( and like me, a few of the participants were actually over 50),. Now, maybe, the most difficult part of this most amazing journey - returning to civilization. Our boys were fully phone and device free for the entire trip - and as I sit on a bus taking us all now from Cimarron to Albuquerque - it makes me melancholy to see a few of the kids plugged back in. Many are just fully crashing in their seats and understandably so. This was genuinely challenging and genuinely exhausting. At the farewell campfire last night - the folks at Philmont pointed out something else - there is a real legacy element here. Scouts have been hiking and learning and bonding in Philmont for over 85 years. That is a lot of miles and memories. Really proud to be part of that community now. Going to take a day or so to get home - count up all the bug bites - shave - and get ready to join you all back on the air later this week.

I have been away and I needed to catch up. I don’t know what you did last night but I binged all 10 episodes of season two of @thebearfx and in this era of peak TV - I simply cannot think of anything better. What an absolutely phenomenal show and what a critical example of how fine writing and fine acting matter most. Like most TV shows the majority of speaking roles are given to men but it is the women in “The Bear” that give this series such incredible heart and soul. Molly Gordon @mollsterg pictured here becomes a star overnight with her role as a girlfriend who offers both her love and more importantly her encouragement to the tortured chef Carmy who is the lead of the series. The great @ayoedebiri is every young person trying to pursue their passion and their talent. My single favorite moment of the second season belongs to Liza Colon-Zayas @lizacolonzayas_lcz in a wordless and priceless reaction to Ayo when her character is offered a promotion. It is difficult to convey an all encompassing feeling of professional pride but Liza does so in the most remarkable way.  Abby Elliott @lilcutieforever is one of many metronomes reminding all of us that a huge amount of time and money are on the line. My comments here echo a series of well deserved rave reviews and I will quote briefly from James Poniewozik and his words in @nytimes . James writes that the lesson of “The Bear” is - “There is also *taking* care, learning discipline, doing things the hard way because it is the right way. But here it is simply firm and honest. Try again, try again. It’s unsparing, but it comes with the belief that you can do better because you are better.”
I love that sentiment. I LOVE this show. Far and away the best thing I have seen on TV or the big screen all year. “The Bear” is on @hulu now. It is remarkable.
null

Hard to believe we are almost the same age. Congratulations to @comedyandmagicclub in beautiful Hermosa Beach. Club is celebrating 45 years of entertaining especially good looking crowds. Happy to be there last night for part of their birthday celebration. Special shows all through July with 20 comedians taking the stage. Slightly shorter sets but a very full show. Stand-outs on Saturday night - @luzpazosfunny  Luz Pazos originally from Peru - very funny and the incredible shrinking man @billygardell Billy Gardell from “Mike and Molly” who has dropped over 150 pounds - but says he misses his heavyset trousers because they were so easy to step into and out of…..and getting your legs caught in skinny jeans is a nightmare. Billy related that fashion foible anecdote far better on stage than I just did here. Live comedy when it is good, is great….tickets don’t break the bank at all….and you can bike down there if you choose. Can’t wait for my next visit.

Eagle Cake. Soon-to-be Eagle Scout. Happy Birthday to my youngest, our son Colby. I have shared a lot of our Scouting adventures and without belaboring the point - when Amirah Kassem was on the show earlier this week with her remarkable offerings from @flourshop - I had to mention my son had a birthday coming up and….look. When I was giving Amirah a brief bio of Colby she had a slew of creative cake suggestions. If you saw her appearance with us on the air, you’ll recall that Amirah grew-up baking with her Mom and that her sincere goal is to make every single day seem like a special celebration- like a birthday. Well she did that for us earlier today. P.S. My wife loved the packaging and home delivery. And I neglected to mention the most important thing - underneath the great Eagle decoration was an absolutely delicious cake. Yum. Thanks so much Amirah!

Current show business labor battles understandably prevent the principals from promoting their work - but I have to tell you that @theatercampthemovie is flat out great. Very funny, and if you have spent even a moment on stage or backstage in any kind of school production I think you will howl. Which is exactly what happened just a short while ago at the sold out showing I took the family to in Century City. And while I would have laughed quite a bit if I saw this alone on a streaming service - the laughs were richer and better because the whole theater was laughing - several times - and to chuckle in a room filled with strangers I think does the heart good. This movie is very big hearted - which I also appreciate and two cast members from @thebearfx are both standouts. The great @mollsterg Molly Gordon is having an unequaled hot streak not only starring in the film but she co-wrote and co-directed it too. Also @ayoedebiri has a smaller role that she pulls off incredibly well with both words and facial expressions. Young @criticschoice winner @official.alankim Alan Kim is also fantastic.  If you can sing one song from three different musicals - that is probably the base amount of musical theater knowledge you need to enjoy “Theater Camp” which was made for 1/50th of the catering budget of “Mission Impossible” and may satisfy certain audiences far more than that film does. Among the many lessons Hollywood may or may not heed this summer is we need rawer and fresher and funnier small movies far more than installment #10 of some faded franchise. I love to laugh and “Theater Camp” really delivers.

How it started - how it’s going. So pleased and proud and grateful with - here I go again - with another aspect of becoming an Eagle Scout. Each Scout is responsible for something called an “Eagle Project.” Where you plan, fully participate and supervise a building project. Thanks to an initial introduction from @meganhenderson , we learned all about the @redeyeinc Watts Empowerment Center an absolute miracle of a community center. The good folks needed a new wall of cubbies - places for kids to put their backpacks. My son and his Scout pals (and his sister) got to work. And after all the steps - getting the plans, the materials, building and finishing and painting - finally we made the delivery and as you can see it fits right in and will serve local kids for a very, very long time. Super special thanks to our friends @airtaskerusa who found us a fantastic work-worker to help us with all we didn’t know - and there is a lot we didn’t know…..but we know now. Most especially the real satisfaction of building something from start to finish and seeing a backyard project fully completed and put to work. By the way, what happens every single day at the Watts Empowerment Center is extraordinary and deserves your attention and support. This site on IG @redeyeinc can tell you all about it and how you can help.  Great feeling to see our Eagle Project standing tall in the hallway where so much good takes place.

location.city_name: Beverly Wilshire, Beverly Hills (A Four Seasons Hotel)

social_posts.post_text: We took many photos at the local Los Angeles Area Emmy Awards tonight - but never mastered the art of getting the shadows off our faces. Fun to be dressed up with so many of my KTLA friends. I think I have succeeded in tagging everyone featured in these pics. @marcussmithca @frankbuckleytv @mtelly @wendyburch @leilashalhoub @claudine_s @thejessicaholmes . Our pal @chercalvin and team took home an especially huge Emmy for a story she did about sky-diving where she actually jumped out of a plane. Otherwise KTLA scored in spirit if not in actual hardware. @michaelapereira did a great job hosting the whole thing - a nearly impossible task. My favorite Emmy moment was not tonight but several years ago when the ceremony was held in an auditorium at the TV Academy HQ in North Hollywood. A beloved @dairyqueen was about a block away - and during an especially long part of the ceremony, I had to get a blizzard for myself and I was sitting behind the great @colleennbcla and offered to buy her a sundae too - and she said “yes.” A great honor to make that purchase for someone I like and admire so much. Tonight no ice cream, (and for me no Emmy’s) but the rewards of this career never end. Happy to be with so many of my friends and colleagues tonight and congratulations to all the winners!

I don’t believe I have ever met actress Inga Swenson who we lost today at 90 years of age. But I have a sweet story about the show that Inga was an integral part of. Some of you might remember “Benson” with the great Robert Guillaume. A spin-off from the classic “Soap” series, Guillaume was the much-smarter-than-his-employer Benson DuBois, the butler. Inga was also seen in “Soap” but on “Benson” she had a new and bigger role playing Gretchen , a German cook. “Benson” ran for 7 seasons and Inga was nominated for an Emmy 3 different times. I bring all of this up because when I was in college, I spent my junior year abroad in Sweden. I was studying the “business of Abba” who at that time had surpassed Volvo as Sweden’s most profitable company. As an America abroad in Sweden - all the locals were so interest in everything about our country. And their single biggest nationwide interest - “Benson.” The Swedes loved Benson, beyond belief. It was the #1 show on TV there and viewership was so massive that on the weekday night that it aired - I think a Tuesday or Wednesday - restaurants complained of being empty because everyone stayed home to watch “Benson.” I always thought that was the funniest thing. That Benson was so big in Sweden. Of course as I discovered in learning more about Inga today - while she was born in Nebraska, her dad was a native of Sweden and was knighted by Swedish King Gustav V. So maybe the Swedes were so obsessed with “Benson” in part because they considered one of the stars a native daughter of sorts. Inga also did a lot of other notable work in movies and on stage. I wonder if she is being mourned in Sweden today as well.

Moral dilemma .  A friend of mine who lives in PV hosted a really nice dinner party at his house last night. So inspired I was by the surroundings I am taking a lovely bike ride in the area. It’s all going so well until it isn’t. Giant flat suddenly in the rear tire. Don’t know if I ran over something or maybe the extra girth from the dinner party last night. Here is the problem. With my big flat tire I am just a few blocks from my friends house. Do I lumber over there and hope he gives me a ride home , allows me borrow his own bike, knows how to fix what looks like a fatal flat.  Or, since he just hosted this nice bash less than 24 house ago - don’t be a bother, take my lumps, and figure out another alternative solution.  Like so many people - I hate to be “that guy” the one who over imposes. What should I do?

Oh no. Into the @hallmarkchannel vortex again. We have plans tonight but “Hearts In The Game” has drawn me in. Hazel and Diego were high school sweethearts - but it didn’t work out. Diego became a professional baseball player. Hazel a big shot NYC publicist. Now they are brought back together as Diego attempts to rehabilitate his career with a major profile piece for “Hudson and Park”
Magazine. But - Hazel and Diego, Diego especially still have feelings for each other. Look how they look at each other when Diego tries to teach Hazel how to throw a fastball. Will this former couple ever get to first base again….or beyond. Now I am sucked in and there is still at least an hour to go……

Our day @disneyland . First a quick shout out to @themagicalmillennial_ - who covers Disneyland food and beverage on the daily - and who, like me, recognizes the genius of the Boyzen Apple Freeze. Kids and dad loved the rides, and I appreciate there are still small touches of the Disney magic focusing on the art and craft that built the company and the parks to begin with. This is the first time in a very long time that I have been to the park as a regular patron. No TV crew nor live broadcast to generate any special treatment. So here is my take for good or for ill.  The rides are great. We did the trio of “Star Wars” rides and that “Rise of the Resistance” is especially remarkable. We also enjoyed the Grizzly River Rapids, Soaring Over The World, Mission Breakout, It’s A Small World, and a few others. But, and this I think is important, three of the rides we went on, all had maintenance breakdowns while we were in line. Both Radiator Springs Racers and Matterhorn Bobsleds were broken down for the whole day. Among all the recent layoffs did they send too many repair people home? Now how did we manage to get on so many rides  on a rather crowded Friday.  We purchased that Genie+ pass, for $25 bucks apiece, and because the “Rise” line was so formidable, I paid another $25 for the “Lightning Lane.” I appreciate the time savings - but also felt my pocket was really picked and I recognize that most people can’t keep unloading 25 dollars willy-nilly. So is the park in danger of becoming prohibitively expensive? That horse may have already left the barn. One other gripe - to “manage” Disneyland in 2023 - you really need your smartphone, maybe too much. I think it is a shame that I spent so much time in the ‘Happiest Place On Earth’ doing what I do in less happy environments - looking at my phone screen. Also, you “need” to use your phone so much you may well run out of charge. Bring an extra battery. Even with all of the above, if I had a chance to spend another day with the kids at Disneyland, I would grab it.
One Sam can really sing , the other really can’t. Emmy nominee Sam Ryder blows us all away with a very touching song from the finale season of “Ted Lasso.” Full interview @ktla_entertainment

If you are not out celebrating national cinema day - I am - $4.00 movie tickets - any theater , any show , all day today - allow me to offer a surprising recommendation from @netflix , the absolutely terrific and very big hearted “You Are So NOT Invited To My Bat Mitzvah.” Warm and winning - the whole @adamsandler family delivers really great performances - most especially his real life daughters. In 2000 Sandler made a dreadful movie - “Little Nicky” and I wrote and broadcast a blistering review - which seemed to stick his craw for years. I was banned from interviewing him, etc.  Maybe now we can find our way back to one another. Obviously Adam himself has clearly demonstrated real acting chops in some recent dramatic efforts - and there is no denying his enormous global popularity. What impresses me the most - and I am not one who touts my religion on my sleeve - is Adam is creating material, especially here, that shows several treasured Jewish rituals in a loving light. I went to Hebrew School on Pico Blvd two afternoons a week and on Sunday’s for years. And while my own Bar Mitzvah was certainly very modest by movie standards - I remember it as a proud day for my entire family. Maybe my favorite part of this movie was reminding me of my daughter Darcy’s Bat Mitzvah - one of  the most moving days of my entire life. What Adam Sandler has helped to facilitate here is not only “good for the Jews,” but good for anyone who wants to enjoy a genuinely entertaining movie. Really happy we watched it together and enjoyed it so much.
We sort of offer our guests at KTLA a light morning snack. @phil.rosenthal points out - it is not nearly enough.

On the very top of the list of Husband specific “Honey-do’s” is - “can you please fill the propane tanks for the BBQ.” Task completed. Spectacularly beautiful day in the ‘bu .  Always the single smartest thing to do - stay in town during Holiday weekends. Let everyone else leave.

One of us here is 74 years young … listen to the always amazing age-defying Rick Springfield. Rick playing live later this month at the You Tube theater. Here is one way to stay young. Play ALL the instruments on your newest album yourself - which is just what Rick did.

I love this. @sammicohen has directed the excellent “You Are So Not Invited To My Bat Mitzvah” movie for Netflix. The young filmmaker was even younger when we first met. They were 7 years old and they were on an elementary school field trip to KTLA. This struck such a cord in me. When I went to Westwood Elementary school we took the best field trips, including one to KNBC studios in Burbank. They had a giant size almost all white news set that looked like a spaceship. I was mesmerized by it and I will never forget sitting in anchorman Jess Marlow’s chair and thinking “This is the greatest job ever.” Turned out that I was right for me. Sammi saw the future too when they first visited with us many, many years ago. Wow. Full conversation @ktla_entertainment .

social_posts.post_text: We shared the news of Don Barrett’s passing on the show earlier today. I wish you could have known him. One thing that brings people together are common interests. Fantasy Football. Taylor Swift. Hiking by the beach. Don and I shared a common interest. Radio in Los Angeles. His LARP (Los Angeles Radio People) column and website was a treasure trove of news and gossip, updates and remembrances of the on-air talent that at one point made Los Angeles the best live radio market in the world. When I was in High School I worked at 93 KHJ - which was basically KIIS-FM before KIIS-FM. I was “in the room” when a young DJ from Memphis was hired for a then unheard of $100,000. His name - Rick Dees. I have worked on the air for KHJ, KNX, KABC, KLSX (daily after Howard Stern) and KkGO. I love local radio and have been really sad to see so much of it devolve and decline. Don Barrett’s column was a celebration of when radio was great  and the really talented people who made it great. And Don was great. Always upbeat and encouraging - and helpful. Offering sincere and welcome advice. I had never heard of Avila Beach - an incredibly beautiful coastal community near San Luis Obispo until Don retired there. He loved it there and loved the life he enjoyed with his wife Cherie.  I don’t think I ever shared with Don how much his professional work and personal help meant to me. I am doing that here and now. Thanks Don Barrett - off of our air at the age of 81 - but always in our hearts.

We are BACK……at least for a while. Please alert your friends and the rest of the world. KTLA is on DirecTV right now!!! Thank you for your patience. Can’t wait to reunite with so many of you on Monday. But you can watch my friends on the weekend show right now!

Sphere here. Tonight is the world premiere of this most innovative of venues - but the key question to me - when U2 takes the stage - how will the Sphere sound? Are there special acoustic qualities to a completely “round” space? What will the visuals be like?  If this Sphere experiment works - I believe the plan is to build other spheres elsewhere around the world. Super excited for the show just a few hours from now.

About last night.  A particularly happy part of my job is being able to check out the latest and greatest in live entertainment in Los Angeles and elsewhere - Las Vegas is often on the itinerary and understandably so. But I am not a connected “insider” like our @meganhenderson and pal Lauren Sivan. Of course thanks to their “pull” not only was I able to hang with the ladies and @davidspade back stage - but enjoyed a very funny show with David and @nikkiglaser . Maybe the best part - a group of ladies sitting behind us - and as both Nikki and David shared their stories these gals would shout “tell it” and laugh harder than almost anyone in the sold out @venetianvegas showroom. A really fun night. What is the over/under for Megan to be at the anchor desk at 4 am on Monday morning?

Our greatest honor ever - @lastweektonight and John Oliver feature our @ericspillman and @meganhenderson and @henrydicarloktla5 and @richontech in an extended riff on our coverage of a story involving John himself and a protest on reddit . As typical of New York based media @lastweektonight displays a shocking degree of a complete lack of familiarity with our show which truth be told has broken so many barriers that actually make their show possible. Still, we are glad they are watching.

“stay in the gym and keep it sexy.” Sage advice from the truly great @davidoyelowo - a wonderful actor involved in a wonderful to support the education of girls in Nigeria. Complete conversation is @ktla_entertainment . David O. Like all of us, is cautiously optimistic that the SAG strike will be ending soon.

One of those days. Ever had so much activity in one day it could fill an entire week. Lunch today with @brookeshields as she spoke with such refreshing honestly and candor about her mental health struggles and successes. I felt lucky to be there along with a rapt audience all brought together by @chocchildrens - who announced dramatic plans to expand their mental health services  for children and teens.  Then a quick scoot up the 405 and to the west for a beautiful wedding of our @ktla_entertainment producer Marie and her now husband Bobby. Incredibly thoughtful and romantic ceremony - a fun photo with several colleagues who are all friends. Don’t worry - we will have lots of video of Brooke and her extraordinary remarks and Marie and her extraordinary wedding all on our @ktlamorningnews on Monday morning. A really moving day - and thank goodness I have two days to recover from it all.

Another @bike_ms in the books. A weekend filled with camaraderie and gratitude. The best weather imaginable - oh, and the best bikes thanks to our friends @rocknroad . Both @ericspillman and @mkupbykellywilliams rode state of the art “acoustic” bikes - light and powerful - while @lynne_spillman and I had the tiniest of electric boosts - which not only makes the ride that much more enjoyable, and frankly doable. Thanks to @iamspecialized for the great gear. We learned this year that @ktla has been the media sponsor for 26 years which means that our proud association with #BikeMS started in 1997. This year our ride will bring in over two million dollars. Over the years the ride has raised tens of millions and among the very tangible results of all that dough - this year we had more riders who actually have multiple sclerosis join us. In bikes acoustic and electric and recumbent -  hard to imagine  something as moving as seeing people push their pedals all day for two days. It’s really something. We have such a great time and we are especially appreciative of our @ktlamorningnews and @ktlaweekendam for giving us the time - year after year - to tell the story of this great event. Our goal for next year - to “widen the tent” and invite more people to take part in the ride. All the logistics are expertly handled for you - and the scenery and support are just extraordinary. Can’t wait for our 27th year and really hope you will join us.

And now a word from our sponsors. Our #BikeMS ride relies on a variety of partners. Many have been with us for years and we deeply appreciate their support. We want to welcome two new friends to the fold. Our pals @vanpowers.bikes have donated a brand new very slick top of the line e-bike to serve as an additional inducement and reward for our riders who generate even more donations after the ride. Someone is going to win this beautiful bike. And, we have all won thanks to the community spirit of the good folks @raisingcanes most especially their local restaurants in Vista , Camp Pendleton and San Marcos. If you stopped at Buccaneer Park in Oceanside you thrilled as I did to Cane’s on hand and some great chicken sandwiches. As I type this I can still taste the very refreshing glasses of lemonade that I enjoyed. It is a wonderful feeling to have some partners who have the willingness and the means to support our good cause. Looking forward to seeing you both next year!

With Britney Spears and Justin Timberlake’s past relationship dominating the headlines this week, our Hollywood correspondent @Samontv gives the lowdown. 

#ThisMorning

The ties that bind. Taking a few days to tour some colleges with our youngest daughter. And while these factors should not be the criteria when selecting a school - I was especially impressed with the neckwear on one campus and the food services at another. One of the real pleasures of parenthood is, if you are lucky enough, to have the opportunity to participate with your child as they select the school(s) best suited to their skills and desires. I have never felt that often overwhelming “college panic” - there are so many great schools and as my mother used to say “there is a lid for every pot.” The one thing that makes me feel privileged for having a good job and a tad guilty at the same time - the incredible and I know for many - the overwhelming cost of a four year school. Our last college graduate wrapped up her studies as a member of the class of 2023. Tuition and room and board prices have really jumped up since she started college in 2019. And it just makes me think of how many more families are likely priced out of so many more schools. And…on the other hand…to take a tour and see your own perspective student really spark to the amazing offerings of one school or another is a great experience. And those two ties pictured here were actually a true bargain compared to the other logo wear at the student store. Happy College Application Season everyone!

Busy times in the Big Apple. The best thing about the decidedly very concentrated nature of New York City is that you can accomplish quite a bit in one day. My Tuesday included Two TV live shots including one from the new-ish CNN world headquarters at Hudson Yards - A great ‘what if’ meeting that may result in an exciting new project - My Brooklyn based daughter has a keen knack for restaurant selection and have enjoyed some fantastic meals together including an amazing dinner tonight - and a great Broadway show “Shucked” that I bet will find its way to Los Angeles in the next year or so. 12,000 + steps and since it’s NYC - all in a suit. There is a unique energy here.

Spirits up - tiles down. Welcome to the World Series of Mahjong. Not just anyone can play - Mahjong masters from around the country - including several from Southern California had to qualify to spend 12 solid hours and countless rounds of play to emerge victorious and claim a sizable grand prize. Friday @ktlamorningnews our world exclusive coverage of the World Series everyone really cares about. Special thanks @marcussmithca for his support and encouragement in bringing you the stories no one else would dare cover. The entire @ktla_entertainment team working overtime to bring you our live and special report on Friday’s show. I still can’t quite figure out how to play but the people, and there are hundreds here, who are deeply into it - are forever fans.

Halloween update! Feel very lucky to live in a neighborhood that still deeply values trick-or-treating. An entire group of grown-ups clear the street of cars - and five bags of candy later we are nearly cleaned out. Two other notes. Best costume goes to a neighbor who is pregnant in real life and saluted Rihanna by emulating a bare belly outfit that she had worn during her pregnancy. Also a candy update. I like twizzlers but apparently I am the only one. Many selective kids avoided the offered red licorice. Biggest hit - Reese’s Peanut Butter Cups.

“All I Want For Christmas” is an amazing ticket giveaway for @mariahcarey and her amazing Holiday concert. Two nights @hollywoodbowl - plus a great date at @yaamava too. Later this week my in depth conversation with “The Queen Of Christmas,” which is, by the way, a moniker that she did not come up with and has decidedly mixed feelings about. Where will Mariah herself spend the Holidays and what does she hope to find under the tree. All will be revealed. And yes - no special effects - Mariah actually does sparkle in person.

Really enjoyed the great Rob Reiner documentary on his BFF Albert Brooks. “Defending My Life” premiered tonight on @hbo and @hbomaxes . Best part for me - incredible clips of Albert on a slew of classic variety shows from Flip Wilson to Dean Martin and many more. Plus 30+ appearances with Johnny Carson. In one interview Larry David speaks of meeting Albert at a party and Albert was very complementary about Larry’s work and Larry came home feeling like he had really made it. I have a similar story. In 2001 the then St. Regis hotel in Monarch Beach had a huge star studded opening party. It was a real blowout and a lot of prominent people were there. Late in the evening and much to my very pleasant surprise Albert Brooks approached me and went on and on about how much he enjoyed our @ktlamorningnews . He said he watched and enjoyed our entertainment reports and all the interviews. And I said, “Thank you, and if you enjoy the show so much we would absolutely love to have you on the show.” And in the best and funniest blow-off I have ever received Albert Brooks immediately replied. “Even though I have never been on the show, I *feel* like I have been on.” It is an encounter I will never forget. The documentary shows many more unforgettable moments in Albert’s amazing career. Maybe we can get him to actually come on our show now. I sure hope so.

This story is, I swear, absolutely true. When a guest comes to visit us at KTLA one must first pass through a labyrinth of security at the gate guarded entrance to our lot. Once inside there are many specific entrances to get to our studios. When one arrives they may meet a receptionist, or another security guard, or one of our staffers. Someone who works on our show. Then, after the guest is here, the @ktla_entertainment team and I are alerted to their arrival. We will receive a phone call or get a top-line message. Occasionally a staffer will come to where the team and I sit, in an area known as ‘the lower newsroom’ and give us an in-person update. That happened today when the guest featured with me in this photo arrived. The exact phrase that was said to me, and I quote word for word. “Sam there is some sort of ‘getaway cat’ here to see you.” Of course the “Getaway Cat” turns out to be Hello Kitty.  I transpose numbers all the time when I am jotting down a phone number. Or I will mix up a letter or two when typing a script or a post. But this - turning Hello Kitty into Getaway Cat is a new one for me. And I have been laughing about it all day. By the way @hellokitty has a new deal with @apple so her cultural dominance will continue. Thanks for coming by for the visit today.

He did it. They all did. My son Colby is now an Eagle Scout. Fantastic ceremony last night for our Troop 223 - as Colby and two dozen of his fellow scouts made the major migration. It is an incredible feat - one involving years of merit badges, deeply memorable camping trips and high adventures. Scouting offers a monumental program and I know both myself and my son really benefited from the experiences and the fellowship. Could not help but to share the great news on our show this morning.

This is authentic festive seasonal fun. Opening night at @holidayroad . A genuinely immersive Holiday light show experience. Very best part - you bundle up and WALK through the displays. Plenty of families with strollers and lots of couples holding hands too. Must buy tickets in advance on-line and  the whole thing seems very well thought out. Located at King Gillette Ranch in deep Calabasas, about 20 minutes or so off the 101. We had a really good time. Just search “Holiday Road Calabasas” and all the info you need will pop right up. Merry, Merry

Degrees of “done”-ness. A tale of two fries. Hickory Burger @applepan tonight and what appears to be a formalization of what I thought was an off-menu item. I asked for “double cooked” fries and was told now I could get either regular fries , “well done”
or “Very well done.” Hard to get used to any changes at The Apple Pan. I picked the middle option. Always love going there.

Happy Hanukkah!!! We have had the soccer ball menorah since I first started coaching @ayso_soccer 20+ years ago. As it is celebrated over eight nights - I have always felt that Hanukkah is sort of a quieter version of Christmas - which is usually concentrated on one big evening and one big day. Many people this year have asked me how, as a Jew, I am feeling about things going on now in the world. First and foremost I am feeling grateful that my mother - born a Jew in Germany - was the rare exception who escaped the Nazis and was separated from but ultimately able to reunite with both her parents and two brothers in a safer and better place. This place - America. So whatever experiences that I may rarely encounter with genuine antisemitism are nothing compared to what she and her contemporaries experienced.  Maybe the shameful exposure of the Ivy League college presidents in the last few days continues to open people’s eyes to the grim reality that one of my father’s favorite phrases “just because you’re paranoid doesn’t mean they aren’t out to get you” might be true. I think many marginalized groups face prejudice….but on this first night of Hanukkah I choose not to think of exclusion, but rather the happy gathering of family and friends to celebrate what Jews believe was an ancient miracle. Here’s hoping to some modern day miracles that include more genuine understanding and tolerance of all people. Including my people.

In my day you could tell if you had been admitted to the college of your choice if the envelope that arrived at your home, was thick or thin. So much for width based announcements. My daughter Darcy received her good news first via personal phone call, then a follow-up email, and just today with a large envelope that did not leave any mystery. You did it indeed. She received a second envelope saying “Congratulations” from an institution I am not entirely sure she even applied to. Her two older sisters each went to fine schools and I think deeply benefited from their college experiences. Impossible to believe that next fall we will send another one off. Despite all the crazy and unnecessary hype - there are so many fantastic options - every kid that wants to will find their appropriate place. Here’s to the class of, can you believe it, 2028.

social_posts.post_text: Magic Maui Moments - Perhaps the best weather I have ever enjoyed here - and made the most of the day. A little rehearsal never hurts - so we did a ‘tech run through” of our @criticschoice movie nominations - which you can watch LIVE at 9:15 am Pacific time on Wednesday morning. Thanks to @pixibeauty for their excellent new skin and sun care products. Giving our award a needed SPF 50 spray. And lastly the beaches at sunset are filled with family and photographers getting that perfect holiday picture. Speaking of perfect our amazing Come To Maui giveaway provided by our hosts @fsmaui happens on TV on Thursday. Aloha!

social_posts.post_text: Now we’ve done it. Thursday on our @ktlamorningnews our most amazing giveaway in perhaps forever . 5 nights on the club floor level of the @fsmaui . AND …the most romantic dinner for two. You meet the chef in advance and curate the menu together. Select the decor and did anyone say “engagement” “renewal of vows” “Babymoon” or “Best First Date Ever.” You need to watch the whole show on Thursday and if you can’t stay until 11 am….DVR the whole show. You do not want to miss this.  Oh, I have heard from so many who have checked the LAX-OGG airfares especially in January and beyond. Incredibly cheap. Maui is open and is ready to welcome you with open and appreciative arms. Come visit or WIN a trip tomorrow.

Good-bye to the Baron. Mark Kriski gave the name “Baron Von Fahrenheit” to one of the single most beloved members of our entire @ktlamorningnews staff, Warren Hohmann. Warren was a “day-one” staffer on our show and worked with us for over 32 years. Mark also called him “Texas” as a salute to his home state, his friendly accent, and a red pick-up truck he drove for years. Warren ran the traffic and weather department, and he deeply cared about the look of the reports and the quality of the information. And….and….he was flat out hilarious on our air. Repeatedly. In skit after skit after skit. No one made me laugh harder. He was really a genius. Now that heart and humor are at rest. We learned that Warren passed away on Friday. We will remember Warren on the air on Monday. But every single one of these pictures brings a bright smile to my face. He brought so many smiles to so many. We love you Warren, and thank you. This show would not be what it is without your countless contributions to it.
KTLA - TV Entertainment Anchor. "Today” 9 Network Australia, ITV "This Morning."  Emmy Award Winning Host. Book a call with me  intro.co/SamRubin
